Don't create toast messages from non-UI thread.

This seems to work on some devices, but it's not technically correct

than sorry, especially since these messages were used in exceptional

title: Don't remove VI constructors used via reflection with ProGuard.
message:
Don't remove VI constructors used via reflection with ProGuard.

Fixed #236.

It turns out that ProGuard (which is only used on the release build and
not the debug builds that I typically test with), was being too
aggressive. It stripped out the constructors for some of the
VehicleInterface classes, so we weren't able to create instances of
those clases. Because ProGuard could never find a time when those
constructors were used, it stripped them out. When the factory tried to
create a new BluetoothVehicleInterface instance, it would get that
error.

The constructors are never used explicitly because they are constructed
using reflection at runtime in the VehicleInterfaceFactory. The reason
for this is so that the Enaber can send a message to the background
processing running the VI connection threads, and it doesn't require a
hard coded conditional to find the right class for the VI.

This updates the ProGuard configuration to not strip out any public or
protected functions in the com.openxc package - it's all open source
code, so we don't need to be concerned with obfuscation, and the
codebase is small enough to not need to worry about optimization too
much. I confirmed that with these classes explicitly kept in the
ProGuard config, it connects just fine.

title: Add map pruning typically handled automatically by Multimap.
message:
Add map pruning typically handled automatically by Multimap.

With a Multimap, removing a key-value pair, where that value is the last one for the key, removes that key. Switching to a map instead of a Multimap, no such 'automatic' functionality exists because the MessageListenerGroup instance is still associated with that key, even if it contains no listeners, so you have to tell the map to delete it manually.

get a NoClassDefFoundError when registering the Bugsnag token. From
Maven, it works fine. I think this has to do with JDK 7 support, since
the Bugsnag library is compiled with 1.6. However, even if I rewrite the

to work. For now, we just catch the error here and continue. The release
builds are done with Maven.

title: Only allow at most 1 vehicle interface to be active via the Enabler.
message:
Only allow at most 1 vehicle interface to be active via the Enabler.

This is a rather large change with these primary goals:

    * Instead of checkboxes, use a ListPreference so at most one VI type
         can be selected at once in the Enabler.
    * Only enable the data source preferences for each VI if that VI is
        selected.
    * Don't enable the USB source by default in the VehicleService

title: Only poll native GPS if connected to a vehicle.
message:
Only poll native GPS if connected to a vehicle.

Instead of creating the NativeLocationSource in the VehicleManager's
process, it is created in the VehicleService process - this allows it to
be notified when vehicle interfaces are connected and disconnected, so
it can know when to stop waiting for GPS updates from Android.

title: Preserve nulled, default value for fields in DiagRequest.
message:
Preserve nulled, default value for fields in DiagRequest.

When sending over the AIDL, we would lose the value 'null' for the
mMultipleResponses field - it would be changed to 'false'. That would
cause it to be inclueded in JSON output, even though it's the default
value and can safely be left out.

title: Don't re-connect BT if we are already making a connection.
message:
Don't re-connect BT if we are already making a connection.

The problem is that when we detect a new device, we were restarting the
connection attempt task, but in the process we would lose reference to
an existing thread that was making connection attempts.

1. The first thread is blocked waiting for a socket connection attempt to
fail (it started too soon, before the device was available)o
2. The device is discovered or connected, and we kick off another
connection thread.
3. The new connection thread immediately succeeds and you get an active
connection. Yay!
4. The old thread fails and since it assumes it's the only thing around,
it kills the connection we just made.

The fix is pretty simple - don't reset connection attempts unless we've
already given up.

Fixed #126.

title: Break out of a possible infinite loop with invalid JSON.
message:
Break out of a possible infinite loop with invalid JSON.

I think this may have been the root of many odd Bluetooth problems. In
some cases, we could load a partial message as JSON but it would have
corrupted field names, and at some point the "field" in this function
would be null and we would loop forever. I noticed this because when
testing the foreground service notification, I was not getting the
"disconnected" callback from the BT data source if I unplugged the VI
abruptly.

title: Don't remove Bluetooth/Network interfaces when Enabler closes.
message:
Don't remove Bluetooth/Network interfaces when Enabler closes.

Fixed #22.

The VehicleService running in a remote process is in charge of these, so we
don't need to shut them down when the Enabler closes. If you shut it down, it
means that whenever you switch away from the Enabler the connection to the
interface is lost.

title: Use common byte stream handling code for Bluetooth and USB.
message:
Use common byte stream handling code for Bluetooth and USB.

Because we have a socket stream with Bluetooth, we can use BufferedReader and
the nice readLine method. I tried implementing this for USB in the
bufferedreader branch with a custom InputStream, but the synchronization
required in my first attempt really killed performance.

In an effort to have the data sources use the same code, I've reworked the
Bluetooth source to use our custom newline-separated message parser in
BytestreamDataSourceMixin.

title: Search for the USB device every time the USB thread starts.
message:
Search for the USB device every time the USB thread starts.

This fixes a problem where if the USB source is start()ed, then stop()ed, then
started() again -- all while the USB device is plugged in -- we never try to
connect to it again.

The old workflow was this:

* When the USB source is created, initialize a connection to the device. Also
    start listening for unplug/plug events so we can detect a USB device being
    plugged in, and start up the USB thread when we detect that.

Of course, what if the source is restarted (but without calling the constructor
again), and the USB device remains plugged in? We don't try to connect.

The fix is to try and initialize the device when the thread starts, not when the
USB source object is created.

title: Don't throw NoValueException from Measurement.getValue().
message:
Don't throw NoValueException from Measurement.getValue().

This is an attempt to minimize the amount of boilerplate code required to access
a single measurement from the vehicle. Previously, every call to
Measurement.getValue() required wrapping in a try/catch block for the
NoValueException. This is because Measurement inherited from NoneData which
enabled measurements to exist with no value. You could programatically check if
they had a value or not before using them.

The motivation for this is that sometimes when the system isn't ready yet, it
can't give you a value for a requested measurement. In an effort to not throw
spurious errors, it was returning a blank measurement.

However, the common use case for OpenXC is asynchronous, and the system doesn't
really need to call your measurement listener if it knows the measurement has no
value. Therefore the "no value" error only really needs to happen when you
synchronously query for a measurement and we can't return one.

This commit moves the NoValueException from Measurement.getValue() to
VehicleService.get(), and removes the NoneData class.

title: Listen for USB attachment intents in a proxy Activity.
message:
Listen for USB attachment intents in a proxy Activity.

This does receive the Intent, but the act of opening up either the activity or
the pop-up to confirm that the activity should start pauses the underlying app
(e.g. VehicleDashboard) and thus the VehicleService and RemoteVehicleService
lose their bound client and exit. So when this activity sends our custom
"refresh devices" intent, the UsbVehicleDataSource isn't around to actually
receive it.

title: Defer measurement notification to new threads - a heavyweight solution.
message:
Defer measurement notification to new threads - a heavyweight solution.

This avoids making the data source block waiting to return from the callback.
This commit also adds a lock in each thread to make sure only one notification
is going out to the callbacks at a time, since the RemoteCallackList doesn't
allow this.

A better solution will be to dump the updates into a queue which has only one
long-lived thread to process it and make the notifications.

title: First unsuccessful stab at an AIDL interface.
message:
First unsuccessful stab at an AIDL interface.

The use of generics is really complicating things - they are not well supported
by the Parcelable interface. I am going to branch off and try making every Unit
parcelable, at the expense of a ton of boilerplate.
